According to Article 68 of the EU AI Act, the scientific panel of independent experts is established to support the enforcement activities under this Regulation. The specific roles and responsibilities assigned to the scientific panel are as follows:

1. The Commission shall make provisions on the establishment of a scientific panel of independent experts by means of an implementing act adopted in accordance with the examination procedure referred to in Article 98(2).

2. The scientific panel shall consist of experts selected by the Commission on the basis of up-to-date scientific or technical expertise in the field of AI necessary for the tasks set out in paragraph 3.

3. The scientific panel shall advise and support the AI Office, in particular with regard to the following tasks:

(a) Supporting the implementation and enforcement of this Regulation as regards general-purpose AI models and systems, in particular by:

(i) Alerting the AI Office of possible systemic risks at Union level of general-purpose AI models, in accordance with Article 90;
(ii) Contributing to the development of tools and methodologies for evaluating capabilities of general-purpose AI models and systems, including through benchmarks;
(iii) Providing advice on the classification of general-purpose AI models with systemic risk;
(iv) Providing advice on the classification of various general-purpose AI models and systems;
(v) Contributing to the development of tools and templates;

(b) Supporting the work of market surveillance authorities, at their request;
(c) Supporting cross-border market surveillance activities as referred to in Article 74(11), without prejudice to the powers of market surveillance authorities;
(d) Supporting the AI Office in carrying out its duties in the context of the Union safeguard procedure pursuant to Article 81.

4. The experts on the scientific panel shall perform their tasks with impartiality and objectivity, and shall ensure the confidentiality of information and data obtained in carrying out their tasks and activities.

5. The implementing act referred to in paragraph 1 shall include provisions on the conditions, procedures and detailed arrangements for the scientific panel and its members to issue alerts, and to request the assistance of the AI Office for the performance of the tasks of the scientific panel.

According to Article 59 of the EU AI Act, personal data lawfully collected for other purposes may be processed solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox when the following conditions are met:

1. The AI systems shall be developed for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person in one or more of the following areas:
   (a) public safety and public health, including disease detection, diagnosis, prevention, control and treatment and improvement of health care systems;
   (b) a high level of protection and improvement of the quality of the environment, protection of biodiversity, protection against pollution, green transition measures, climate change mitigation and adaptation measures;
   (c) energy sustainability;
   (d) safety and resilience of transport systems and mobility, critical infrastructure and networks;
   (e) efficiency and quality of public administration and public services.

2. The data processed are necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data.

3. There are effective monitoring mechanisms to identify if any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing.

4. Any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox are in a functionally separate, isolated and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider, and only authorized persons have access to those data.

According to Article 59 of the EU AI Act, personal data lawfully collected for other purposes may be processed solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox when the following conditions are met:

1. The AI systems shall be developed for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person in one or more of the following areas:
   (a) public safety and public health, including disease detection, diagnosis, prevention, control and treatment, and improvement of healthcare systems;
   (b) a high level of protection and improvement of the quality of the environment, protection of biodiversity, protection against pollution, green transition measures, climate change mitigation and adaptation measures;
   (c) energy sustainability;
   (d) safety and resilience of transport systems and mobility, critical infrastructure and networks;
   (e) efficiency and quality of public administration and public services.

2. The data processed are necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data.

3. There are effective monitoring mechanisms to identify if any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing.

4. Any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox are in a functionally separate, isolated, and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider, and only authorized persons have access to those data.

According to Article 58, the implementing acts for AI regulatory sandboxes must include common principles on the following issues to ensure uniformity across the Union:

(a) eligibility and selection criteria for participation in the AI regulatory sandbox;
(b) procedures for the application, participation, monitoring, exiting from and termination of the AI regulatory sandbox, including the sandbox plan and the exit report;
(c) the terms and conditions applicable to the participants.

According to Article 11(1) of the EU AI Act, the technical documentation for an AI system must include the following information:

1. A general description of the AI system, including:
   (a) its intended purpose, the name of the provider, and the version of the system reflecting its relation to previous versions;
   (b) how the AI system interacts with, or can be used to interact with, hardware or software, including with other AI systems, that are not part of the AI system itself, where applicable;
   (c) the versions of relevant software or firmware, and any requirements related to version updates;
   (d) the description of all the forms in which the AI system is placed on the market or put into service, such as software packages embedded into hardware, downloads, or APIs.

Therefore, as a developer of an AI system, you must ensure that your technical documentation includes a clear and comprehensive description of the intended purpose of your AI system, as well as how it interacts with other hardware or software systems. You must also provide information on the versions of relevant software or firmware and any requirements related to version updates. Finally, you must describe all the forms in which your AI system is placed on the market or put into service.

The purpose of processing personal data in AI regulatory sandboxes is solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person in areas such as public safety and public health, protection of the environment, energy sustainability, safety and resilience of transport systems and mobility, critical infrastructure and networks, and efficiency and quality of public administration and public services. 

The processing of personal data in AI regulatory sandboxes must meet certain compliance requirements, including: 
- The data processed must be necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data;
- Effective monitoring mechanisms must be in place to identify any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing;
- Any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox must be in a functionally separate, isolated and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider and only authorized persons have access to those data. 

Additionally, for the purposes of the prevention, investigation, detection or prosecution of criminal offences or the execution of criminal penalties, including safeguarding against and preventing threats to public security, under the control and responsibility of law enforcement authorities, the processing of personal data in AI regulatory sandboxes shall be based on a specific Union or national law and subject to the same cumulative conditions as referred to in paragraph 1.

According to Article 58(1) of the EU AI Act, the implementing acts must include common principles on the following issues related to the AI regulatory sandboxes:

(a) eligibility and selection criteria for participation in the AI regulatory sandbox;
(b) procedures for the application, participation, monitoring, exiting from and termination of the AI regulatory sandbox, including the sandbox plan and the exit report;
(c) the terms and conditions applicable to the participants.

Furthermore, the implementing acts referred to in paragraph 1 must ensure that:

(a) AI regulatory sandboxes are open to any applying provider or prospective provider of an AI system who fulfils eligibility and selection criteria, which shall be transparent and fair, and that national competent authorities inform applicants of their decision within three months of the application;
(b) the data processed are necessary for complying with one or more of the requirements referred to in Chapter III, Section 2 where those requirements cannot effectively be fulfilled by processing anonymised, synthetic or other non-personal data;
(c) there are effective monitoring mechanisms to identify if any high risks to the rights and freedoms of the data subjects, as referred to in Article 35 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and in Article 39 of Regulation (EU) 2018/1725, may arise during the sandbox experimentation, as well as response mechanisms to promptly mitigate those risks and, where necessary, stop the processing;
(d) any personal data to be processed in the context of the sandbox are in a functionally separate, isolated and protected data processing environment under the control of the prospective provider and only authorised persons have access to those data;
(e) providers can further share the originally collected data only in accordance with Union data protection law; any personal data created in the sandbox cannot be shared outside the sandbox;
(f) any processing of personal data in the context of the sandbox neither leads to measures or decisions affecting the data subjects nor does it affect the application of their rights laid down in Union law on the protection of personal data;
(g) any personal data processed in the context of the sandbox are protected by means of appropriate technical and organisational measures and deleted once the participation in the sandbox has terminated or the personal data has reached the end of its retention period;
(h) the logs of the processing of personal data in the context of the sandbox are kept for the duration of the participation in the sandbox, unless provided otherwise by Union or national law;
(i) a complete and detailed description of the process and rationale behind the training, testing and validation of the AI system is kept together with the testing results as part of the technical documentation referred to in Annex IV;
(j) a short summary of the AI project developed in the sandbox, its objectives and expected results is published on the website of the competent authorities; this obligation shall not cover sensitive operational data in relation to the activities of law enforcement, border control, immigration or asylum authorities.

According to the EU AI Act, high-risk AI systems related to migration, asylum, and border control management include:

- AI systems intended to be used by or on behalf of competent public authorities or by Union institutions, bodies, offices, or agencies as polygraphs or similar tools;
- AI systems intended to be used by or on behalf of competent public authorities or by Union institutions, bodies, offices, or agencies to assess a risk, including a security risk, a risk of irregular migration, or a health risk, posed by a natural person who intends to enter or who has entered into the territory of a Member State;
- AI systems intended to be used by or on behalf of competent public authorities or by Union institutions, bodies, offices, or agencies to assist competent public authorities for the examination of applications for asylum, visa or residence permits and for associated complaints with regard to the eligibility of the natural persons applying for a status, including related assessments of the reliability of evidence;
- AI systems intended to be used by or on behalf of competent public authorities, or by Union institutions, bodies, offices, or agencies, in the context of migration, asylum or border control management, for the purpose of detecting, recognizing or identifying natural persons, with the exception of the verification of travel documents.

It is important to note that these high-risk AI systems must be designed and developed in such a way that they achieve an appropriate level of accuracy, robustness, and cybersecurity, and that they perform consistently in those respects throughout their lifecycle. Additionally, they must be registered in a secure non-public section of the EU database and be subject to specific requirements for transparency, human oversight, and accountability.

According to Article 53(1), point (a) of the EU AI Act, providers of general-purpose AI models must draw up and keep up-to-date the technical documentation of the model, which shall contain, at a minimum, the information set out in Annex XI. Annex XI specifies that the technical documentation shall contain at least the following information as appropriate to the size and risk profile of the model:

1. A general description of the general-purpose AI model including:
(a) the tasks that the model is intended to perform and the type and nature of AI systems in which it can be integrated;
(b) the acceptable use policies applicable;
(c) the date of release and methods of distribution;
(d) the architecture and number of parameters;
(e) the modality (e.g. text, image) and format of inputs and outputs;
(f) the licence.

According to Article 68(3) of the EU AI Act, the scientific panel will advise and support the AI Office in the following tasks:

(a) supporting the implementation and enforcement of this Regulation as regards general-purpose AI models and systems, in particular by:
(i) alerting the AI Office of possible systemic risks at Union level of general-purpose AI models, in accordance with Article 90;
(ii) contributing to the development of tools and methodologies for evaluating capabilities of general-purpose AI models and systems, including through benchmarks;

(b) supporting the work of market surveillance authorities, at their request;

(c) supporting cross-border market surveillance activities as referred to in Article 74(11), without prejudice to the powers of market surveillance authorities;

(d) supporting the AI Office in carrying out its duties in the context of the Union safeguard procedure pursuant to Article 81.

According to the EU AI Act, when deciding whether to impose an administrative fine on a Union institution, body, office, or agency in the context of an infringement, and when deciding on the amount of the administrative fine in each individual case, all relevant circumstances of the specific situation shall be taken into account. The following factors are considered:

(a) the nature, gravity, and duration of the infringement and its consequences, taking into account the purpose of the AI system concerned, as well as, where appropriate, the number of affected persons and the level of damage suffered by them;

(b) the degree of responsibility of the Union institution, body, office, or agency, taking into account technical and organizational measures implemented by them;

(c) any action taken by the Union institution, body, office, or agency to mitigate the damage suffered by affected persons;

(d) the degree of cooperation with the European Data Protection Supervisor in order to remedy the infringement and mitigate the possible adverse effects of the infringement, including compliance with any of the measures previously ordered by the European Data Protection Supervisor against the Union institution, body, office, or agency concerned with regard to the same subject matter;

(e) any similar previous infringements by the Union institution, body, office, or agency;

(f) the manner in which the infringement became known to the European Data Protection Supervisor, in particular whether, and if so to what extent, the Union institution, body, office, or agency notified the infringement;

(g) the annual budget of the Union institution, body, office, or agency.

Based on these factors, appropriate actions are taken to address the infringement, including the imposition of administrative fines, implementation of technical and organizational measures, and cooperation with the European Data Protection Supervisor.

Notified bodies must inform the notifying authority of the following regarding Union technical documentation assessment certificates:

(a) any Union technical documentation assessment certificates, any supplements to those certificates, and any quality management system approvals issued in accordance with the requirements of Annex VII;

(b) any refusal, restriction, suspension or withdrawal of a Union technical documentation assessment certificate or a quality management system approval issued in accordance with the requirements of Annex VII;

And they must report any circumstances affecting the scope of or conditions for notification. This information is stated in Article 45(1) of the EU AI Act.

According to the EU AI Act, the factors that may be considered in determining administrative fines for infringements include:

1. The nature, gravity, and duration of the infringement;
2. The intentional or negligent character of the infringement;
3. The degree of responsibility of the infringer, taking into account technical and organizational measures implemented by them;
4. The financial gain or losses avoided as a result of the infringement;
5. The harm caused to individuals or society, including the extent of any discrimination or bias;
6. The previous infringements committed by the infringer;
7. The cooperation of the infringer with the supervisory authority to remedy the infringement and mitigate its possible adverse effects;
8. The categories of personal data affected by the infringement;
9. The manner in which the infringement became known to the supervisory authority, in particular whether, and if so to what extent, the infringer notified the infringement;
10. The measures taken by the infringer to mitigate the possible adverse effects of the infringement;
11. The adherence to approved codes of conduct or approved certification mechanisms; and
12. Any other aggravating or mitigating factors applicable to the circumstances of the case.

According to Article 47 of the EU AI Act, the EU declaration of conformity for a general-purpose AI model must include the following details:

1. The identification of the general-purpose AI model and its provider;
2. A reference to the relevant harmonized standards or other technical specifications used;
3. A statement that the general-purpose AI model conforms to the requirements of the EU AI Act;
4. The date of the declaration;
5. The identity and signature of the person authorized to sign the declaration on behalf of the provider;
6. The address of the provider's registered place of business;
7. Any relevant additional information, such as the intended use of the general-purpose AI model and any limitations on its use.

The EU declaration of conformity must be made available to the AI Office and national competent authorities upon request.

According to Article 54 of the EU AI Act, if the Commission receives a qualified alert from the scientific panel, it may take one or more of the following actions:

1. Request the provider to provide additional information or to carry out additional tests or studies;
2. Request the provider to take appropriate measures to mitigate the risks identified in the qualified alert;
3. Request the provider to suspend or withdraw the AI system from the market or use, or to restrict its use, until the risks identified in the qualified alert have been addressed;
4. Require the provider to inform users and other relevant stakeholders of the risks identified in the qualified alert and the measures taken to address them;
5. Require the provider to provide regular updates on the measures taken to address the risks identified in the qualified alert;
6. Require the provider to carry out a recall of the AI system from the market or use, or to take other appropriate corrective measures, where necessary, to ensure the safety and fundamental rights of users and other affected parties.

The Commission may also take any other appropriate measures to address the risks identified in the qualified alert, including imposing administrative fines or penalties, or initiating legal proceedings.

According to the EU AI Act, when adopting delegated acts concerning safety components of AI systems, the following factors should be taken into account:

1. The state of the art in AI technology and its foreseeable evolution;
2. The risks associated with the intended use of the AI system;
3. The potential impact of the AI system on the health and safety of persons, on the environment, and on fundamental rights;
4. The need to ensure that the AI system is transparent, explainable, and allows for human oversight;
5. The need to ensure that the AI system is robust, secure, and resilient;
6. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate levels of human control;
7. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate levels of testing, verification, and validation;
8. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate levels of monitoring and reporting;
9. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate levels of documentation and record-keeping;
10. The need to ensure that the AI system is subject to appropriate levels of training and education for users and operators.

These factors are intended to ensure that AI systems are developed and deployed in a safe and responsible manner, and that they are subject to appropriate levels of oversight and control.

According to Article 29(3) of the EU AI Regulation, conformity assessment bodies must submit the following information with their application for notification:

1. The name and address of the conformity assessment body;
2. The identification number assigned to the conformity assessment body by the national accreditation body;
3. The scope of the conformity assessment activities for which the conformity assessment body is seeking notification;
4. The name and address of the conformity assessment body's legal representative in the Union, if applicable;
5. A description of the conformity assessment procedures and methods used by the conformity assessment body, including any relevant technical specifications or standards;
6. A description of the conformity assessment body's quality management system, including any relevant technical specifications or standards;
7. A list of the conformity assessment body's personnel, including their qualifications and experience;
8. A statement of the conformity assessment body's independence and impartiality, including any conflicts of interest that may arise;
9. A statement of the conformity assessment body's financial and organizational resources;
10. A statement of the conformity assessment body's liability insurance coverage;
11. A statement of the conformity assessment body's compliance with the requirements of the EU AI Regulation and any relevant technical specifications or standards;
12. Any other information required by the national accreditation body.
